Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pour the @water{300%ml}(for the rice) into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling,
turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave
to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to
cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{260%g}. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}.

Cook until the chicken is browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Add the garlic and @Zanzibar style curry powder{2%tsp} (add less if you'd prefer things
milder) to the chicken. Stir-fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200%ml} and @chicken stock paste{10%g}. Bring to the boil,
then lower the heat and simmer gently until the chicken is cooked through and the curry
has thickened slightly, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add a splash of @water{} if the curry looks a bit dry.

Meanwhile, zest and halve the @lime{1/2}.

When the rice is ready, fluff it up with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest.

Once the curry is cooked, add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a handful at a time
until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Squeeze in some lime juice and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Taste and add more
lime, salt and pepper if needed.

Spoon the zesty rice into #bowls{} and top with the fragrant chicken curry.

Enjoy!